    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Congratulations on your new home purchase! Escrow can be a bit confusing, but I'm here to help. Your earnest money is typically held in an escrow account, which is a separate account managed by your real estate agent or a third-party escrow company. It's like a temporary holding cell for your earnest money, where it's kept safe until the closing date, when it's released to the seller as a condition of the sale. Think of it like a goblin's treasure chest, where your earnest money is stored until the time is right to release it. \n\nOnce you sign the contract, your earnest money is usually deposited into the escrow account, and it's then used to cover various closing costs, such as title insurance, appraisal fees, and other expenses. The escrow company will hold onto it until the closing date, when it's disbursed to the seller as a final payment. It's a bit like a goblin's promise to deliver the treasure, but in this case, the treasure is your earnest money.",
