    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let me break it down for you in simpler terms.\n\nAn escrow agent, also known as an escrow company, is a neutral third-party service that holds and manages funds on behalf of the buyer and seller. Their primary role is to ensure that the transaction proceeds smoothly and that all parties fulfill their obligations.\n\nIn the case of earnest money, the escrow agent holds the funds until the closing date, when they're disbursed to the seller as a condition of the sale. The escrow agent typically handles tasks such as:\n\n* Receiving and holding the earnest money deposit\n* Paying out closing costs and other expenses\n* Coordinating with the title company and other parties involved in the transaction\n* Providing a secure and transparent accounting of the funds\n\nThink of the escrow agent as a referee, ensuring that the game (the real estate transaction) is played fairly and that all parties follow the rules. They're not directly involved in the sale, but rather provide a necessary service to facilitate the process.",
